The fishing industry is responsible for most of the marine debris issue. If we remove seven key items we find on every beach in Hong Kong,

Polystyrene Boxes
Polystyrene Fishing Floats
Plastic Fishing Floats
Fuel Oil Cans
Plastic Baskets/Trays
Abandoned/Dumped Fishing Nets
Plastic Water Bottles (major contributor)

the majority of the marine debris will be removed.

Why Govts are not putting more pressure onto holding the fishing industry to be more accountable is probably the biggest issue and needs to be addressed.

A lot has changed since the last World Environment Day.

From collecting 14,800+ tonnes of plastic waste to now crossing 45,700 tonnes, it’s been a long journey of grit and purpose.

None of this would’ve been possible without the relentless efforts of our waste collectors, the workers at our facilities, and the many hands behind the scenes who show up every single day.

But our impact hasn’t just been environmental, it’s social too. 
·	More scrap shops supported. 
·	More informal waste workers uplifted. 
·	More livelihoods strengthened.

This World Environment Day, we extend our heartfelt thanks to our brand partners, supporters, ground teams and the entire Plastics For Change family for helping us move closer to a cleaner, fairer world. 

We remain deeply committed to build systems that create both environmental and social change! 

#worldenvironmentday2025 #peopleandplanet #circulareconomy♻️ #plasticsforchange #fairtradeplastic

Tiny, invisible, and everywhere!

Microplastics are now part of what we eat and drink.

Trace amounts of plastic that are too small to see, too widespread to ignore have been found in seafood, salt, drinking water, and even human blood.

This crisis goes beyond environmental damage:
→ Marine life mistakes plastic for food
→ Contaminated seafood reaches our tables
→ Ecosystems are thrown off balance
→ And most critically, human health is at risk

Recycling plays a crucial role but it’s not enough on its own.

To truly address plastic pollution, we must reduce plastic at the source and create systems that stop waste before it starts.

Priya has been part of our waste collection team in Pondicherry for a year now. 

She’s also a mother of two — both kids are back in school.

But what truly stayed with us was what she does after work.

Once she’s done collecting plastic waste for the day, Priya sits down and handcrafts chains, selling them to local shops to support her family a little more.

No fuss. No complaints. Just quiet determination.

We’re proud to work with women like Priya and through our entrepreneurship programs, we are supporting their dreams, both within and beyond the waste ecosystem.

#WomenOfChange #FairTradePlastic #InclusiveEconomy #Entrepreneurship #PeopleAndPlanet #PlasticsForChange

Plastics For Change & Garnier Empowering Women Waste Collectors in India

She spent years collecting plastic. Now, for the first time, she holds a bank account in her name.

For Annal, a waste collector from Tamil Nadu, every day meant navigating the streets, collecting plastic to make a living. Like millions in the informal waste sector, she worked relentlessly.

Without access to a bank account, her earnings slipped through unstable hands borrowed, spent, or lost in informal credit cycles.

Financial inclusion in informal sector is the key to stability, dignity, and the ability to plan for a future beyond mere survival.

And now, Annal became the first in her community to open a bank account. It means:
security for her earningsaccess to fair financial systems, anda bridge from survival to stability.
When businesses invest in people and the environment, the circular economy thrives.

Thanks to Garnier India (L’Oréal) for this collaboration.

Fair trade is a business model that drives long-term value.

In today’s global economy, circularity cannot succeed without fairness at its core. 

If we want supply chains to be future-proof, they must be inclusive, traceable, and built on dignity, from the first mile to the final product.

- Fair wages.
- Safe working conditions.
- Gender equity.
- Environmental responsibility.

These are the structural foundations for ethical sourcing and resilient operations.

On World Fair Trade Day, I’m reflecting on this: What good is circular design if the people in the loop are still exploited?

Let’s rewire our systems!

At Plastics for Change, we’ve embedded all 10 Fair Trade principles into our everyday operations, proving that it’s possible to scale circularity while uplifting lives across the value chain.

If you’re a brand looking to build ethical, human-inclusive supply chains using ocean-bound plastic, we’re ready to partner.

Fast fashion isn’t cheap - the planet pays the price.

Mountains of clothes - some with tags still on - wrapped in plastic, dumped and forgotten.

Shipped across oceans. Never worn. Never recycled.

That’s the dirty secret of fashion.

But it doesn’t have to end this way.

We work with fashion brands to recycle their plastic packaging and waste, turning it back into usable material.

From single-use to circular.

Because clothes weren’t made to die in landfill - and neither was the plastic they came in.

latestPosts.caption:
When we throw away bottles without emptying them, someone else pays the price.

At Plastics for Change, we’ve seen what this looks like—
→ Hours wasted draining leftover liquid
 → Slower sorting at scrap shops
 → Unnecessary effort for women already working long, hard days

What takes us two seconds can save them hours.

Because true sustainability goes beyond materials—it includes those who make it possible.

So before you throw it away, take a moment to empty it.

Because someone else shouldn’t have to.

– Waste into livelihoods.
– Supply chains into ethical, fair, transparent ecosystems.
– And bring global brands closer to communities they once overlooked.

This World Fair Trade Day, we’re proud to spotlight our workers at our recycling centres in India.

Following the principles of the World Fair Trade Organization (WFTO), we’ve built a model where every person in our supply chain is seen, heard, and valued.

𝐓𝐡𝐢𝐬 𝐄𝐚𝐫𝐭𝐡 𝐃𝐚𝐲, 𝐥𝐞𝐭’𝐬 𝐩𝐚𝐮𝐬𝐞 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐚𝐬𝐤, 𝐰𝐡𝐚𝐭 𝐝𝐨𝐞𝐬 𝐬𝐮𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐢𝐧𝐚𝐛𝐢𝐥𝐢𝐭𝐲 𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐥𝐥𝐲 𝐦𝐞𝐚𝐧 𝐟𝐨𝐫 𝐛𝐮𝐬𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐬𝐬?

It’s no longer just about what your product is made of but also about who made it possible.

𝐎𝐯𝐞𝐫 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐲𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐬, 𝐰𝐞 𝐛𝐮𝐢𝐥𝐭 𝐚 𝐭𝐫𝐚𝐧𝐬𝐩𝐚𝐫𝐞𝐧𝐭 𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐞𝐭𝐡𝐢𝐜𝐚𝐥 𝐬𝐮𝐩𝐩𝐥𝐲 𝐜𝐡𝐚𝐢𝐧:
- Our materials come from ocean-bound plastic collected by our waste collectors
- Ensure safe working conditions and paid fair, transparent wages.
- Our business model recognizes, includes, and uplifts them through our social additionality programs.

And our fair trade-verified materials are fully traceable, connecting global brands to a supply chain that meets rigorous environmental and social compliance standards.

This Earth Day, we’re doubling down on what we do best:
Creating a future where business, impact, and human dignity go hand in hand.

Businesses can be a force for good when they care for both people and the planet.

As part of our ongoing initiative with Estée Lauder, we distributed e-tricycles to our waste collectors in Chennai.

This brings significant benefits to waste collectors who often walk over 6 to 7 kilometers a day to collect plastic waste.

With this initiative: 
→ More distance can be covered
→ More plastic waste can be collected
→ More income can be earned
→ And most importantly, health conditions are significantly improved

We’re grateful to our supporters and brand partners for making this possible.

#sustainability #circulareconomy♻️ #plasticsforchange #recycling #explorepage #fyp
